<p class="article__lede">
The choice between Medicare Advantage and Original Medicare with a Medigap supplement is the single most consequential financial decision most Americans make in their 60s. It is also, for most people, a decision that quietly locks in for life. The window to switch between the two systems without medical underwriting closes six months after you first enroll. After that, in most states, you can technically switch back to Original Medicare anytime — but you cannot get a Medigap policy at any price the carrier chooses to charge, and they can charge whatever they want, or refuse you outright, based on whatever pre-existing conditions you have accumulated since 65. The choice you make at 65 is the choice you tend to live with at 85, when the consequences of that choice matter the most.
</p>

<p>
That fact alone — that the decision is effectively one-way for most people — would justify a careful, data-driven comparison. What you get instead, from most sources, is marketing. Medicare Advantage plans spent roughly $7 billion on television advertising in 2024, more than nearly any other consumer category. The brokers who help you enroll are typically paid more for placing you in Medicare Advantage than for placing you in Medigap. The websites that compare plans for free are funded by the same broker economy. The conversation is heavily distorted toward Advantage. The numbers underneath are not.
</p>

<p>
This article is the cornerstone article underneath the Medicare sub-pillar of the Money pillar. We are going to walk through what Medicare Advantage and Medigap actually are, the five dimensions where they differ in ways that matter, the case for each, the 2026 changes that have shifted the calculation, the most expensive mistakes, and — at the end — the honest answer for most healthy 65-year-olds. The honest answer is not the answer the television commercials are giving you. It is also not the answer most local Medicare brokers are giving you. We will tell you why.
</p>

<h2>The 15-second version</h2>

<p>
<strong>Original Medicare</strong> is the federal program. It has two main parts: Part A (hospitalization) and Part B (outpatient medical). It pays roughly 80% of approved costs. The remaining 20% has no out-of-pocket maximum, which is why nearly everyone on Original Medicare buys a <strong>Medigap</strong> policy (also called Medicare Supplement) from a private insurer. The Medigap policy covers the gaps in Original Medicare. You also separately enroll in a <strong>Part D</strong> drug plan. Total monthly cost in 2026 for most healthy 65-year-olds: roughly $310 to $475 per month combined (Part B premium + Medigap + Part D), with very low out-of-pocket costs after that.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medicare Advantage</strong> (also called Part C) is a private insurance product approved by Medicare. It replaces Original Medicare entirely. Most plans bundle Part A, Part B, Part D, and additional benefits (dental, vision, hearing, sometimes gym memberships and grocery allowances) into a single policy. Many plans advertise $0 monthly premium beyond the Part B premium that everyone pays. Total monthly cost in 2026 for the lowest-premium plans: roughly $185 per month (just the Part B premium). The catch is on the back end: limited networks, requirements for prior authorization on many procedures, and an annual out-of-pocket maximum of up to $9,250 in 2026 for in-network care, and unlimited for out-of-network in many plan types.
</p>

<p>
The short version of the comparison is this. Medicare Advantage is cheaper when you are healthy. Medigap is cheaper when you are seriously sick. Most people do not know which one they will be five years from now, but they do know what the actuarial tables say: roughly 70% of people 65+ will need significant medical care at some point in their remaining lifetime, and the cost of being in the wrong plan when that happens is in the tens of thousands of dollars.
</p>

<h2>The five dimensions that actually matter</h2>

<p>
The Medicare comparison gets buried under a hundred small differences. The five below are the ones that decide whether the plan you choose at 65 will quietly bankrupt you or quietly take care of you. The rest is marketing.
</p>

<h3>1. Network access</h3>

<p>
<strong>Original Medicare with Medigap</strong> is accepted by roughly 98% of physicians in the United States who accept any insurance. There is no network. Your Medigap policy works with any provider who accepts Medicare, anywhere in the country. You can move to a different state and your coverage is unchanged. You can go to the Mayo Clinic, the Cleveland Clinic, MD Anderson, or any major academic medical center, regardless of where you live. You do not need referrals to see specialists.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medicare Advantage</strong> uses provider networks. HMO plans (the most common type) restrict you to in-network providers, with very limited out-of-network coverage and usually no out-of-network coverage at all except for emergencies. PPO plans allow out-of-network care at significantly higher cost-sharing. Both types typically require prior authorization for major procedures, imaging, and specialist visits. If your trusted oncologist, surgeon, or specialist is not in your plan's network, you cannot see them — or you pay full out-of-network price. If the Mayo Clinic is not in your plan's network, the Mayo Clinic is not available to you. Networks change every year. The cardiologist who is in-network in 2026 may not be in 2027.
</p>

<p>
For people who travel frequently, live in two states, or anticipate needing complex care at a major academic medical center, the network question alone is usually decisive in favor of Medigap.
</p>

<h3>2. Out-of-pocket maximum and predictability</h3>

<p>
This is the dimension where the comparison genuinely cuts both ways.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Original Medicare with Medigap Plan G</strong> — the most popular Medigap plan — gives you an effectively flat-rate medical year. You pay the Medigap premium (typically $130 to $250 per month in 2026, depending on age and state), the Part B premium ($185 in 2026), and the Part D premium ($30 to $80). Beyond that, the only out-of-pocket cost is the annual Part B deductible of $257. After that deductible is met, Medigap Plan G covers 100% of remaining Medicare-approved costs. Your worst-case year and your best-case year are nearly identical financially.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medicare Advantage</strong> has a much wider range. Most plans have a low monthly premium — often $0 to $50 — but you pay copays and coinsurance for every interaction. A specialist visit might cost $35 to $50. A hospital stay might involve $300 per day for the first five to seven days. Chemotherapy or cancer treatment can run thousands of dollars in coinsurance even with the annual maximum. The 2026 federal cap on Medicare Advantage out-of-pocket spending is $9,250 for in-network care, with many plans setting the cap lower (typically $3,000 to $7,000). But you can hit that cap fast in a bad year, and the cap resets every January.
</p>

<p>
For a healthy 65-year-old, Medicare Advantage costs less. For a 70-year-old going through a cancer diagnosis with two surgeries, six months of chemotherapy, and follow-up care, the difference between the two systems can be $8,000 to $9,000 of out-of-pocket exposure per year on Medicare Advantage versus near-zero on Medigap. The Medigap policyholder paid roughly $1,800 more in premiums during their healthy years to insulate themselves from that bad year. For most retirees on fixed income, that insulation is worth more than the premium savings.
</p>

<h3>3. The lock-in</h3>

<p>
This is the most under-discussed dimension and possibly the most important.
</p>

<p>
When you first enroll in Medicare at age 65, you get a <strong>six-month Medigap Open Enrollment Period</strong>. During this window, you can buy any Medigap policy in your state without medical underwriting, regardless of your health. The insurer must sell you a policy at the standard rate. After this six-month window closes, in most states, your guaranteed-issue rights are gone. If you initially enrolled in Medicare Advantage and later want to switch to Original Medicare with a Medigap policy, the Medigap insurer can review your full medical history, charge you whatever they want based on your pre-existing conditions, or refuse to sell you a policy at all. (Four states — Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, and New York — require guaranteed issue year-round; a few others have partial protections. Everywhere else, the lock-in is real.)
</p>

<p>
In practice, this means the choice you make at 65 tends to become permanent. If you enroll in Medicare Advantage at 65 and develop diabetes, heart disease, or any chronic condition by 67, your ability to switch to Medigap is severely compromised. You can switch back to Original Medicare during the Annual Enrollment Period (October 15 to December 7) — that part is easy. What you cannot easily get is the Medigap policy that makes Original Medicare financially manageable.
</p>

<p>
The implication: the Medicare Advantage decision at 65 is bet on staying healthy. If the bet pays off — and for many it does — the financial savings are real. If the bet does not pay off, the cost of the bet is being trapped in a network-restricted plan exactly when you need the freedom of Original Medicare.
</p>

<h3>4. Prior authorization</h3>

<p>
A 2023 Office of Inspector General report found that Medicare Advantage insurers denied 13% of prior authorization requests that would have been approved under Original Medicare rules. The denial rate for post-acute care, including skilled nursing facility stays after a hospitalization, is even higher. A 2022 KFF analysis found that Medicare Advantage enrollees experienced delays or denials of care that the same care would have been approved for under Original Medicare.
</p>

<p>
The practical experience this produces: you have surgery scheduled, but the plan needs to "review" it. The MRI your doctor ordered requires a phone call from your physician's office, which the practice manager will not make for another week. The skilled nursing facility your surgeon recommends after your knee replacement is denied; the one your plan approves is forty miles further away and has worse reviews. None of this happens with Original Medicare and a Medigap policy. Medicare approves care according to medical necessity criteria written into federal regulation. There is no third party between you and your physician's judgment.
</p>

<p>
The administrative friction does not show up in the premium comparison. It shows up in delayed surgeries, denied post-acute care, and physician offices that are increasingly unwilling to accept Medicare Advantage at all because of the documentation burden.
</p>

<h3>5. End-of-life cost exposure</h3>

<p>
Roughly half of an average American's lifetime medical spending happens in the last two years of life. Cancer, dementia, heart failure, and the gradual decline of multiple chronic conditions account for most of it. This is the period where Medicare Advantage and Medigap diverge most sharply.
</p>

<p>
The Medicare Advantage out-of-pocket maximum protects you for one year. If you have a serious illness across three years, you pay the maximum each year — potentially $25,000 or more in out-of-pocket exposure across the period, plus the cumulative effect of denied care, restricted networks, and reduced access to clinical trials or specialized treatment centers. Medigap Plan G, across the same three years, costs you the Part B deductible each year ($257 in 2026) and the premiums. The difference at end of life is often $20,000 to $40,000 in direct out-of-pocket cost, plus the difference in quality of care.
</p>

<p>
This is the dimension that most readers — being currently healthy — find easiest to dismiss. It is also the dimension that, in retrospective surveys of people who have been on both systems through a serious illness, drives the most regret about the original choice.
</p>

<h2>The case for Medigap (which is most people)</h2>

<p>
For most healthy 65-year-olds with stable retirement income, Medigap Plan G combined with a Part D drug plan is the right answer. The reasons:
</p>

<p>
<strong>Predictability.</strong> A Medigap policyholder's annual medical exposure is the Part B deductible ($257 in 2026). That is the worst case. There is no calendar-year roulette. There is no question about what a hospitalization or a surgery will cost out of pocket. Retirees on fixed income need predictable expenses more than they need low average expenses, and Medigap delivers predictability that Medicare Advantage structurally cannot.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Network freedom.</strong> The ability to see any physician in the country who accepts Medicare — and to keep that ability for the rest of your life regardless of where you live or where the best specialists turn out to be — is a benefit whose value is invisible until you need it. Most retirees do, eventually, need to travel for specialized care, or move to a new state for family reasons, or develop a condition that requires an out-of-state academic medical center. Medigap covers all of this.
</p>

<p>
<strong>The lock-in works the right way.</strong> Buying Medigap during the six-month Open Enrollment Period at 65 locks in your guaranteed-issue right at the moment when you are likely to be healthiest. The premium will adjust over time, but no insurer can refuse you, increase your rate based on pre-existing conditions, or cancel your policy. You hold the option that becomes most valuable when your health deteriorates.
</p>

<p>
<strong>The math works for almost any year with serious care.</strong> The roughly $130-to-$250-per-month Medigap premium adds up to $1,500 to $3,000 per year. A single hospitalization, a cancer diagnosis, a heart procedure, or a year of dialysis on Medicare Advantage routinely costs more out of pocket than that. The premium difference between the two systems pays for itself the first time you need significant care.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medigap Plan G specifically</strong> — not Plan F (which is no longer available to new enrollees), not Plan N (which has copays), not the high-deductible variants — is the plan that strikes the right balance for most people. It covers everything except the small Part B deductible. It is widely available. It is competitively priced because so many carriers offer it.
</p>

<h2>The case for Medicare Advantage (which is some people)</h2>

<p>
There is a real case for Medicare Advantage. It is narrower than the marketing suggests, but it exists.
</p>

<p>
<strong>You are 65, healthy, and have a low tolerance for premiums.</strong> If a $130-to-$250 monthly Medigap premium genuinely strains your budget, and you are willing to accept the back-end risk in exchange for lower fixed costs, Medicare Advantage saves you real money in healthy years. The math works if your health holds.
</p>

<p>
<strong>You strongly value the bundled extras.</strong> Many Medicare Advantage plans include dental, vision, hearing, gym memberships (often SilverSneakers), over-the-counter allowances, and sometimes grocery or transportation benefits. The cash value of these extras varies, but for a regular gym-goer, regular dental patient, and active eyewear user, the bundled value can exceed $1,500 to $3,000 per year. Compare against the Medigap premium and the math is closer than it appears.
</p>

<p>
<strong>You live in a region with a strong, narrow integrated system.</strong> If you live in Pittsburgh and get all your care at UPMC, or in Minneapolis and get all your care at HealthPartners, or in Northern California and get all your care at Kaiser, the network restriction of a Medicare Advantage plan inside that system is often invisible to you because you would not have left the system anyway. The integration, the digital tools, and the bundled extras may genuinely add value.
</p>

<p>
<strong>You have employer-sponsored retiree coverage that pairs with Medicare Advantage.</strong> Some former employers, union benefits, and public-sector pension plans subsidize Medicare Advantage premiums in ways that substantially change the math. Read your retiree benefits paperwork carefully before deciding.
</p>

<p>
What you do <em>not</em> have a strong case for Medicare Advantage on: $0 premium as a primary selection criterion, television advertising claims about extras you will not actually use, the convenience of bundled enrollment, or the recommendation of a broker whose commission is higher on Advantage. The case for Advantage rests on the four scenarios above. The case against Advantage is the five-dimension comparison above.
</p>

<h2>The 2026 changes that matter</h2>

<p>
Medicare rules change every year. The 2026 changes that affect the Advantage-versus-Medigap decision specifically:
</p>

<p>
<strong>Part D out-of-pocket cap of $2,100.</strong> Starting in 2026, Medicare Part D enrollees will pay no more than $2,100 out of pocket for prescription drugs in a calendar year, with the option to spread that cost into monthly payments under the new Medicare Prescription Payment Plan. This is one of the most significant Medicare changes in two decades. It dramatically reduces the financial argument for Medicare Advantage plans that bundle Part D, because the catastrophic drug-cost protection that Advantage plans used to provide is now built into every Part D plan, including the standalone Part D plans paired with Medigap.
</p>

<p>
<strong>2026 Part B premium: $185.</strong> The standard Part B premium increased to $185 per month in 2026, up from $174.70 in 2025. The annual Part B deductible increased to $257 from $240. These numbers affect the Medigap math directly, since Plan G covers everything except the Part B deductible.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medicare Advantage out-of-pocket maximum: $9,250 in-network</strong> for 2026, up from $9,350 in 2025 (slight technical reduction due to plan structure changes). Many plans set lower maximums, but the federal ceiling is the worst case for in-network spending. Out-of-network spending in PPO plans can substantially exceed this. HMO plans typically have no out-of-network coverage at all.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Continued network instability.</strong> Several major academic medical centers, hospital systems, and individual physicians have dropped Medicare Advantage contracts in 2024 and 2025, citing administrative burden and reimbursement disputes. The trend is expected to continue into 2026. Networks that look comprehensive on the enrollment paperwork may have meaningfully different composition by mid-year.
</p>

<h2>The most expensive mistakes</h2>

<p>
The Medicare landscape is unusually rich in mistakes that compound for decades. The biggest ones:
</p>

<p>
<strong>Mistake 1: Defaulting to Medicare Advantage because it has a $0 premium.</strong> The premium is the most visible cost and almost always the least important. The real cost of Medicare Advantage shows up years later, in network restrictions and out-of-pocket maximums hit during serious illness. Selecting a plan based on premium alone is the most common, most expensive Medicare error.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Mistake 2: Missing the six-month Medigap Open Enrollment window.</strong> The window starts the month you turn 65 and you are enrolled in Part B. After it closes, in most states, Medigap insurers can underwrite you, charge what they want, or refuse to sell you a policy. Many people enroll in Medicare Advantage at 65 thinking they can "try it and switch later." For many of them, "later" is mathematically possible but practically prohibitive.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Mistake 3: Trusting a broker who only sells one carrier.</strong> Many "Medicare brokers" are actually agents for a single carrier or a small panel of carriers, paid on commission. Their incentives are not aligned with yours. A genuine independent broker will quote you plans from at least eight to ten different carriers, will not push Medicare Advantage by default, and will spend at least an hour on the initial consultation. If the broker quotes you one plan from one carrier in twenty minutes, find a different broker.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Mistake 4: Not enrolling in Part B on time.</strong> If you do not have qualifying employer coverage and you delay Part B enrollment beyond your Initial Enrollment Period (the seven months around your 65th birthday), you pay a 10% lifetime premium penalty for every year you delayed. That penalty applies for the rest of your life. The exception — and it is the only common exception — is if you or your spouse is still working and covered by an employer health plan with 20 or more employees, in which case you can delay Part B and enroll without penalty during a Special Enrollment Period when that coverage ends.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Mistake 5: Choosing a plan based on this year's drug formulary or this year's network.</strong> Both change every year. The plan that covers your blood pressure medication at $5 per month in 2026 may charge $50 per month in 2027. The cardiologist who is in-network in 2026 may not be in 2027. The right comparison is the structural one — Advantage networks change every year by design; Original Medicare with Medigap has no network risk. Not the snapshot of this year's drug list or this year's provider directory.
</p>

<h2>How to actually enroll in 2026</h2>

<p>
Three stages, roughly six hours of work total, spread across two or three sittings.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Stage 1: Use Medicare.gov's plan finder.</strong> Go to <a href="https://www.medicare.gov/plan-compare" rel="noopener" target="_blank">medicare.gov/plan-compare</a> directly. It is the official tool, free, and not funded by broker commissions. Enter your zip code, your current prescriptions, and your preferred pharmacies. The tool will show you every Medicare Advantage plan, every Medigap option, and every standalone Part D plan available in your area, with real prices and real coverage details. Spend ninety minutes here before talking to any human. Most people skip this step and lose the analytical framework that would tell them whether the salesperson on the phone is steering them correctly.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Stage 2: Get an independent broker consultation.</strong> For most readers, the right partner is <a href="https://www.askchapter.org" rel="sponsored noopener" target="_blank">Chapter</a>, which is the rare Medicare broker that pays its agents a salary rather than per-enrollment commissions, removing the structural bias toward Medicare Advantage. Chapter's agents will quote you plans from every major carrier, including Medigap policies, including the ones with no affiliate revenue for the broker. The initial consultation is free. You retain full control over which plan you enroll in. The broker handles the paperwork. <a href="https://www.healthpilot.com" rel="noopener" target="_blank">HealthPilot</a> is a similar independent option with a different broker economics. If you prefer not to use a broker, you can enroll directly through Medicare.gov or through any individual carrier's website.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Stage 3: Enroll during your eligibility window.</strong> Your Initial Enrollment Period runs from three months before your 65th birthday month to three months after — a seven-month window. The Medigap Open Enrollment Period starts the month you turn 65 and are enrolled in Part B, lasting six months. The Annual Enrollment Period for plan changes is October 15 to December 7 each year, with changes effective January 1. Special Enrollment Periods apply to life events (moving to a new state, losing employer coverage). Missing any of these windows has cost consequences that compound for life.
</p>

<h2>The honest answer for most people</h2>

<p>
For most healthy 65-year-olds with stable retirement income and no employer-subsidized Advantage option, the honest answer is:
</p>

<ul class="article__plan">
  <li><strong>Part A.</strong> Free for most people based on work history. Enroll automatically when you turn 65.</li>
  <li><strong>Part B.</strong> $185 per month in 2026. Mandatory unless you have qualifying employer coverage.</li>
  <li><strong>Medigap Plan G.</strong> Roughly $130 to $250 per month in 2026 depending on age, state, and carrier. Buy it during your six-month Open Enrollment Period.</li>
  <li><strong>A standalone Part D drug plan.</strong> Roughly $30 to $80 per month in 2026. Selected based on the medications you actually take, using the Medicare.gov plan finder.</li>
</ul>

<p>
Total monthly cost: roughly $345 to $515 in 2026, depending on Medigap and Part D plan selection. Annual out-of-pocket exposure beyond premiums: the $257 Part B deductible, plus the $2,100 Part D out-of-pocket cap if your drug spending reaches the cap (most people's does not). That is your worst-case year. That is also your best-case year. The predictability is the product.
</p>

<p>
For most people, that combination is what every retirement-planning math model in the country actually recommends when you take broker commissions and television advertising out of the equation. It is the answer that the data supports. It is also the answer that virtually nobody is telling you to your face, because the financial incentives of nearly every party in the Medicare landscape — except yours — point in the other direction.
</p>

<p>
The exceptions are real and named above. Some readers fit them. Most do not.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>What we did not cover (and why)</h2>

<p>
This article is the cornerstone comparison. It does not exhaustively cover three related topics that have their own treatments coming in the Money pillar.
</p>

<p>
<strong>Medicare timing when one spouse still works.</strong> The interaction between an employer health plan and Medicare enrollment is complex and creates significant penalties for people who misread the rules. Forthcoming article: <em>Medicare Timing When One Spouse Still Works</em>.
</p>

<p>
<strong>HSAs in the year you enroll in Medicare.</strong> Health Savings Account contributions must stop in the month you enroll in any part of Medicare. The interaction with timing is its own analysis. Forthcoming article: <em>Health Savings Accounts for Pre-Retirees: The Underused Lever</em>.
</p>

<p>
<strong>The Medicare-Medicaid dual-eligible situation.</strong> For readers with lower retirement income, Medicaid can dramatically change the Medicare math. Different article, different pillar (it intersects with the Legal pillar's Medicaid planning content). Forthcoming.
</p>

<p>
For now: the comparison above. The decision deserves the careful version, not the marketing version.
</p>

